properties.name: St. Louis Union Station Rope Course

reviews.text: Lived in St. Louis a while, customer service is just different than other places. Must have tennis shoes, empty pockets but lockers available. With that said go in and watch people on it to get the idea and technique. Once you get up some areas may be closed and cause congestion but overall it was busy but we got to do everything in the 40 or so minutes. It was a very fun experience, there is a small Little Tykes session for little kids but my 9 year old did the main course. I'm afraid of heights and my palms sweat the whole time but it was fun and had all levels of difficulty. There's a coffee and cookie joint right there too.

We bought tickets a whole day in advance and showed up prior to our time. Since we had time to spare and hadn't eaten breakfast we asked if we could come back and go at a later time.  We were told we could go at any time after our scheduled time.  Turns out, they meant whatever time it was showing on the sign, not with any group.  So we got there 15 minutes after our scheduled time and the next time was 2 hours away.  Contrary to what we'd been told, we couldn't go with any group and would have to wait the 2 hours.  The staff did a terrible job of explaining this and we had based our whole day around this event.  The staff needs better communication around what happens if you miss your time.  What a disappointment!

First day was sold out which is completely understandable. The second day I had my girlfriend's parents take my son to do the small tykes course and they said he was too tall. No harm no foul. We bought tickets that day to come back the next day to do the bigger course with my son. We got there right at open and then they now said that my son was too short to the bigger ropes course. We ended up doing the smaller course. The person running the check in desk has a definite attitude with me for no reason as I was understanding but was trying to explain what happened but clearly did not want to hear it from me and was too busy buried in their phone.

I would highly recommend this to others. Their prices are very reasonable and they have great options.  $15 for the adult course and $5 for the kids course. My kids had a great time and I was able to be in there with them. It was very reasonable and we got to stay in there for a good 25 to 30 minutes. Really fun and a great option.
My grandson LOVED it! It’s very cool, BUT, the staff was too busy playing with their phones and not at all paying attention to what’s going on. So, high marks for the course and low marks for staff.

properties.adr_address: 801 Market St, St. Louis, MO 63101, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Park dotted by lawns, pathways & seating, & notable for its water features, sculptures & video wall.

properties.formatted_address: 801 Market St, St. Louis, MO 63101, USA
properties.name: Citygarden Sculpture Park

reviews.text: I visited park on early Sunday summer morning. So there were just a few people doing yoga and walking with dogs. Judging on trash and empty Hennessey bottles this place was super busy a night before. I liked their sculptures. Very liked their flowerbeds with different kinds of fragrant herbs.  They have interesting water features.

Such a beautiful spot tucked into downtown St. Louis! The garden has pools for splashing, zen spaces, lots of benches, and co art sculptures to enjoy. Enjoy it for free any day!--no matter the season or the weather. There's always something to enjoy at the Citygarden Sculpture Park.

This is a cool, gorgeous city garden right in the heart of STL. It’s a small garden with many artsy sculptures. We visited in
The time of Christmas, and so they have a nice Christmas lighting. We parked the car on the street. It was weekend, and the parking was cheap. The park is small. It doesn’t take much time to take a walk. There are nice spots to take pictures too.
I had a good experience here.  I went on a Friday evening and there were kids playing in the pools.. its a fun space to walk around. ...its right downtown and it's worth checking out

OMG……. So Relaxing and Picturesque…there are Sculptures that you can take photos on or of…. VERY WELL KELPT area. This is a place to go to enjoy the weather, the view of the arch or just to read a book, yoga, meditation. I recommend this location just to enjoy life in general.

properties.adr_address: 4662 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.formatted_address: 4662 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.name: Big Muddy Adventures

reviews.text: Great adventure with a great company. Not only are Mike and Mark great guides, they are always safety first. They provided our group with a safe, fun, relaxing float and overnight camping adventure. The meals they prepared were great and they always had good stories to tell. Top notch company. Go plan your adventure with them!!!

Great time on the evening full moon float. I highly recommend it for locals and those from out of town. Big Muddy strikes a nice balance of providing a quality, informative, guided experience that still keeps a sense of adventure. I'll definitely do another trip with them.

We had so much fun and such a good experience! The staff was very knowledgeable and friendly and it really was a good experience that I would recommended for most ages and types. Floating by the Arch at sunset on a beautiful Friday night was just best. Then to top it off, after the trip they provided a charcuterie snack with a beer or two for good measure.

Fantastic experience! We plan to do the trip again some time. Excellent guides and food. My husband and I are in our 60s and we found the evening perfect. We highly recommend the Full Moon Float experience!
Big Muddy Adventures provided a fun evening, a fantastic dinner and an out-of-this-world experience on the full moon float! We will be coming back!

properties.adr_address: 5595 Grand Dr, St. Louis, MO 63112, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Opened in 1876, this 1,300-acre park includes 3 museums, a zoo, athletic fields & golf courses.

properties.formatted_address: 5595 Grand Dr, St. Louis, MO 63112, USA
properties.name: Forest Park

reviews.text: This park is amazing. The only parks I've been to that compare are Central Park and Golden Gate. It absolutely massive and beautifully designed and laid out. You can spend a few days exploring all there is to see. The art museum and the zoo are both free and world class. I had a great time exploring and taking pictures.

This is a fantastic park.  It is larger than Central Park.  The St Louis Zoo is located here.  The naturescape area is really unique.    I haven't seen that before.  My daughter loved it.  I didn't get to see the boatyard, but I did drive by.  It would be a great area for walking, running, biking, etc.

The park is located just off the highway and only a few minutes from downtown.  Also, the zoo is FREE (unless you consider parking).  I truly wish there was a park like this where I live.

Love this place!! It has great walking trails,  gardens, wooded areas and streams through out the park. Great things for the family;  from a great park, a zoo and discovery animals to play and ride on, and picnic areas.  Every part of the park has something to offer! A planetarium,  boat house, jewelbox, zoo, history and art museum all free to the public. Also a golf course for the adults.

Passing through and made a quick stop here. Dog friendly park. Beautiful area to walk around and see the grounds. Zoo is also in this area. I didn't go there but saw the entrance as I was exiting the park. It was beautiful with metal sculptures.

This is a gorgeous park situated in a perfect part of town. Plenty of trails to walk with benches scattered throughout to rest and enjoy nature. Tennis courts, kayaking, canoeing, golf, trails, benches and plenty of open spaces for kites and picnicking make this entire park a picture-perfect spot to relax and explore.

properties.adr_address: 2000-2030 Alfred Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.formatted_address: 2000-2030 Alfred Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Brookings Exploration Center

reviews.text: Love it! The decor is so neat, and comfortable. There's lots of educational materials that are fun for kids. Games, books, toys and interactive fun. There's also a nice big family restroom as well as a calm room for nursing or chilling out an overtired toddler having a meltdown.

A wonderful variety of interactive stations for children of all ages. Displays and small creature exhibits change seasonally.

During the week, there are quiet spaces for adults to escape to.

Fantastic year 'round but this polar vortex weather has given me another excuse to enjoy all of the activities here with my granddaughter. It amazes me that it's never been crowded here in the winter when I've come!
A great place for kids to play and participate in hands-on learning.
Love coming here.

properties.adr_address: St. Louis, MO 63110, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Free 90-acre zoo featuring animals such as penguins, bears & elephants, plus a train ride (fee).

properties.formatted_address: St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: STL Zoo

reviews.text:
The zoo is free, but the parking is $15.

We started our day with a behind the scenes giraffe tour. I posted a tour review under the link for the giraffes.

We also watched a mini sea lion show. It was a mini show because they are practicing for the full length shows that will start in a couple of weeks.

The zoo is kept clean, and the people who work there seems to really love their jobs. Most of them were very happy to share so much information with us about the animals.  Many of the buildings are historical, with a few that were built for the World’s Fair.

The exhibits had information for each animal. I appreciate the numerous signs asking patrons to not bother/harass the animals, and a phone number to allow anyone who witnesses concerning behavior to report it.

I would love to see most of the animals in bigger enclosures. Even if that meant they had fewer varieties of animals.  I did appreciate that most of the exhibits had a wide variety of live plants and trees in them.

Our funnel cake was delicious. The gift shop staff was very nice. We loved our visit!

Beautiful zoo! And it is free! They charge for a few of the attractions but they are geared more for smaller kids (Dino,  train, petting stingray.) The bird house was one of my favorite exhibits. We also loved the penguin exhibit and how close we were able to get to them.  It felt like we entered their habitat, but without disturbing them. Oh, and the Grizzlies! Really, a great zoo.

Nice zoo. Wasn’t crowded at all.  Very hot out would recommend bringing personal fan or coming on a cool day. Gift shop items were reasonably priced. Also if you choose to touch the sting rays be aware of the fact that there Is no soap to wash your hands with. Everything was good except for the fact that you still need to pay for refills with the souvenir cup otherwise great experience.

Love this zoo!  Been twice now (I don’t live in St. Louis) and it is such a lovely place to visit.  So many happy animals and each species has a well thought out, tailor-made enclosure.  An all around great day out for both kids and adults - and admission is free!  I particularly enjoyed the primates and the butterflies. The butterflies fly around a beautiful flower filled area and there are literally hundreds of them.  You have to check you don’t have one on you when you leave.

It's amazing that you get such a positive experience in a zoo that doesn't charge an entry fee. Great exhibits, great variety of animals and well maintained! Did not spot any animals that showed signs of sickness or malnourishment.

Parking was a little bit of a nightmare so I highly recommend getting there early.
Also the place is massive, definitely not something you'd try and complete in an hour or so unless you're speed walking through the entire facility.

properties.adr_address: 440 N 4th St ste 170, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.formatted_address: 440 N 4th St ste 170, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Top Notch Axe Throwing St. Louis

reviews.text: What a great time. Whole family had such a wonderful time. We threw axes, stars, cards. Staff was great! You can bring your own beer in! We would do it again anytime. If you are in the area make sure you take a few hours and check it out! Short walk from the Arch.. . Thanks for a great time!

We loved our experience at Top Notch in downtown St. Louis. Kenny and Dakota were amazing to work with! We had so much fun from throwing axes to stars to cards. The music really added to the experience and Kenny was playing some good jams! He’s also an expert photographer and captured some fun poses for us! Definitely would go back.

We always have a great time here. It's good for a date, family time, kids, group of friends etc. Staff is pretty helpful, they have a decent variety of knives, axes, hatches, and other items to try and throw. I've taken dates here as well as my children.  Good for all ages. Very expensive but you'll have fun.

This was SO much fun! We were a little worried at first that axe throwing may not be all it was hyped up to be, but we gave it a chance and had a BLAST! Kenny, our instructor, was informative, attentive and kept us on our toes! He always had something to bring to the table that made it a bit more interesting than before. We got competitive and definitely had our inner children brought back to life. We will be back!!

Our first time trying this in St. Louis. They were wonderful! Axe Master Ben was very helpful. He showed us how to throw axes, stars, and playing cards. He helped us when we struggled. There were games to play and target practice! There is soda and water if you get thirsty. We played for about 1 hour and 30 mins. We were all throwing decent by the end of the night. We found parking in a parking garage $2.00 an hour and was not that far to walk. I would go back again!

properties.adr_address: 750 N 16th St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Constantly evolving art installation, playground & discovery center made from found objects.

properties.formatted_address: 750 N 16th St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: City Museum

reviews.text: Amazing place for everyone. Toddlers to bigger kids to teenagers and adults. You could spend hours here and keep finding amazing things. The food isn't crazy experience either so you can spend the day here. They were super great with our large group over the weekend. We had about 90 people in our group and they were super accommodating and there were no issues.

You have got to take your children here! I visited as the parent of adult children. I wish I had taken my kids here. This place is amazing. Be sure to give your kids a quiet break every once in a while because it’s really overwhelming for little ones. The employees are polite and thoughtful and knowledgeable. There’s something for everybody here to see or enjoy. The views from the rooftop are nice. The young man running the Ferris wheel day I visited was very entertaining and really seemed to enjoy his job. I wish someone would check on the antique cabinets because items are falling off the front of the shelves. I’m looking forward to returning

The most redeeming quality of this place is all of the stuff that has been kept out of a landfill.  Props to the artists who’ve created a fun place to explore.

My 80s kid at heart did appreciate that there was a lot of space for free play, climbing, exploring.

But… There were WAY too many people in the facility. My husband commented that this may have been where Covid originated.   I understand that they are making $20-30 per person, so packing them in makes more money. But limiting the number of people would increase the quality of the experience so much more.

Gift shop idea- sell headphones or ear plugs!!!

It felt like half of the facility was food places, gift shops, and kiosks where you can spend more money.

There appears to be plenty of space in the building that isn’t being used. I’d consider visiting again if they open up new spaces to explore.  Otherwise, I most likely won’t return.

Took a 3yo and a 14yo, we ended up spending about 3hours here.  We had so much fun exploring, around literally every turn, corner, nook, and cranny.  Definitely want to return when my toddler is a little older, as I didn't feel safe letting them explore some of the smaller and darker areas.  Some sections seemed a little less tended to than others, but overall things were neat and appeared clean.

City Museum is awesome! I have been visiting it since 2005. It is still as fun as I have gotten older although a little rougher on the knees. The kids always have a wonderful time. You can spend a few hours or an entire day. The rotating exhibits keep things new and interesting. I highly recommend a visit if you are in St. Louis.

properties.adr_address: 4257 Northeast Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA

editorial_summary.overview: 1868 park that shows its history with carriage rides, grass tennis courts, a wading pool & a gazebo.

properties.formatted_address: 4257 Northeast Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Tower Grove Park

reviews.text: Mid winter,  spring is beautiful.  Pavilion's can be reserved and wedding's take place by the fountain at the Piper Palm House.  Great place to have wedding, and family photos.  2 separate playgrounds a small one near Grand Blvd. Larger playgrounds by the tennis courts in the center of the park.  The larger playground has a shallow (like a foot or 2 deep) water pond for the kids in the summer. Friday's are food truck days, and sometimes a farmer's market.  Plenty of trails for biking or walking.

Just such a fantastic park! I am lucky enough to live right across the street and do morning walks where are you encounter lots of friendly joggers on the weekends they have the farmers market which is absolutely amazing. Live music WONDERFUL playgrounds that are well maintained AND a splash pad for summer!

Hands down the place to be on Saturday mornings...where what has be the regions largest Farmer's Markets held just about every week of the year!  It's THE place to get best local products made by artisan and vendors and The finest produce gown and sold by real family farms!  Not to mention how awesome the park itself is!  With so many historically significant pavilions and buildings, and being right next to the botanical garden (originally part of Henry Shaw's property) there are a wide diversity of ornamental and native trees/shrubs, as well as wide open spaces to enjoy a little bit of nature near the heart of St. Louis.

It has a lot of nature in the spring and beautiful structures with beautiful birds and a clean and safe environment. When I go there, I really feel a sense of comfort and different nationalities are seen.

Tower Grove Park is a wonderful place to go for a walk, toss or kick a ball around, hear some music, visit the popup farmers market, food trucks are there periodically and when they're not, there are eateries in walking distance on Grand Boulevard.

properties.adr_address: 4344 Shaw Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA

editorial_summary.overview: A greenhouse dome, a Victorian home & gardens, a butterfly house & more spread across 79 acres.

properties.formatted_address: 4344 Shaw Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Missouri Botanical Garden

reviews.text: A really nice family friendly garden. Current under renovations to welcome center area, looks like a big project that will be amazing when completed. We came on Juneteenth for a free day at the gardens. They often have gardening workshops and the kids area of the gardens is amazing! Tons of fun things to play on, a slash pad, and more! Would come back just for the kids area!

We went to the Garden Glow last Wednesday, and the Garden looks great! The new lobby and front steps blew me away with how amazing they looked. Everything looks so open and modern! I am a big fan of Glow, and of the garden in general. I love how it's set up, and the sense of peace and calm I get from being among all the flora. The new gift shop looks awesome, and I really like all the learning opportunities presented to guests throughout the garden. This is a St. Louis gem that we are so lucky to have!

This is just a review of the Garden Glow for the Holidays.  It's open until 10pm, so the later you go, the less crowds.  When we were leaving at 8:30, it was considerably thinning out.  Lots of very cool light displays.  Very organized as you are directed along a route. The regular garden displays are not open.  Only a portion of the garden is lit up.Nice photo opportunities set up along the way.  It's a little expensive but worth the money at least once. Also a great way to get some fresh outdoor air at this time of year.

I recently had the opportunity to visit the Missouri Botanical Garden, and I must say that it was an enchanting and unforgettable experience. This garden is an absolute must-visit, offering a serene and picturesque oasis right in the heart of the city.

The cherry blossoms were in full bloom during my visit, creating a breathtaking display of delicate pink petals against the clear blue sky. It was the perfect backdrop for leisurely strolls and memorable photo opportunities. The garden's layout is thoughtfully designed, with well-maintained paths that meander through a diverse range of flora and themed areas.

One of the standout features of the Missouri Botanical Garden is its cleanliness. The grounds are impeccably maintained, with pristine walkways and beautifully manicured landscapes. It's evident that the garden staff takes great pride in ensuring the area remains a pristine sanctuary for both visitors and local wildlife.

It was a beautiful space and everyone was so helpful in the lobby area. We happened to go on a festival weekend (Japanese) and it was so much fun! I know my family has already talked about going back in different seasons to see how it changes.
Also -- there are various restrooms, water fountains, and indoor exhibits to see besides the lovely outdoor garden paths.

properties.adr_address: 1854A Russell Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63104, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1854A Russell Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63104, USA
properties.name: Urban Fort Play

reviews.text: This place is definitely geared towards parents. A coffee shop and a place for my kids to have a ball?!! Yeah, I’ll be back . I had the cold brew with chocolate syrup and it was delicious

I had a wonderful time. I have a 9 month old and 6 year old. They both enjoyed themselves. I could see my 6 year old from the infant play area 😊 also invited some of my kiddos for a play date and it went amazing 🤩 truly had a blast.. staff were very friendly.. definitely will be back 😘
What a cool little place to take toddlers for some interactive indoor play time. Also...order beautifully prepared food and beverages (healthy!) while you're there.
Great atmosphere. Food is over priced but my child really loved the play area

With or without the kids, Urban Fort has delicious food and great coffee in a space that is inviting, casual, and comfortable. Check out the warm flaky chocolate croissant and the caprese pannini. Board games for kids and adults. If you've got a kid(s) under 8 and are looking to play and socialize, this is the place. There are tables and chairs off to the side as well as in the thick of the kids area. The staff is friendly and upbeat.

reviews.text:
$34? For a day pass and gear (shoe rental included)

Staff has you sign some waivers and explains how the auto belay system works… then just sends you on your way.

A couple climbs with the auto system, but you’d probably want a (certified?) friend come along for a lot of the climbs.

Came right at open on a weekend. It was busy but not terribly so

Staff was friendly as well

Not impressed. Pricing was inaccurate right off the bat. Top rope test may as well be a lead test, not much difference from other gyms lead. Never had to take an unannounced fall in dozens of different gyms for top rope. Traveling through, glad I only did a day pass. Staff wasn’t very knowledgeable, and nobody ever helped with questions i had. Definitely not beginner friendly, but luckily not beginners. Holds don’t seem to be cleaned much. Boulder area is small with harder than average sets and vague grading. There’s an attitude vibe here, too. At least the top amd lead wall is tall with good moderates. Daughter and I won’t be back.

Extremely friendly staff, very noob friendly but also several extremely advanced walls. Multiple different walls with auto-belays so you don't have to be certified or have a belay partner, an entire section dedicated to bouldering less than 15 feet. Haven't climbed in 10 years, went here yesterday with my wife and immediately felt the same sense of accomplishment as I used to feel back then. Strongly considered a membership and making this my new gym/workout, and if I didn't live an hour away I would have signed us up in a heartbeat.
Love climbing here. If you lead climb, they have a very tall archway to traverse on a couple of routes. It's a smaller gym, but very fun.

Went here around 12 pm on a weekday and it wasn't packed. Took us awhile to figure out where to enter and park. We parked on the street in front of the building. There isn't much parking from what I saw. We have a Groupon for a rental package for two. It included climbing shoes, harness, and chalk pack. They went over a quick introduction to climbing because it was our first time. We climbed on the auto relay walls. These walls are for beginners. The auto relay will catch and lower you down if you slip. We had a blast! I would definitely recommend this place.

properties.formatted_address: Concourse Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Anne O'C. Albrecht Nature Playscape

reviews.text: My one year old and I love this park!! There is so much to explore for any age kid. We especially love playing in the water feature during the summer. It’s our favorite park in the area!

Great place for kids to explore!
*Being towel and clothes if you're going to let your kiddos get wet or play in the mud.

Pros:
Lots of variety
Very spread out so doesn't feel crowded
Encourages creative play and lots of physical activity.
Great climbing for older kids

Caution:
May be difficult for strollers.
Requires a lot of walking. May be tough for anyone with physical restrictions.
Bathroom is available but not very convenient
Some areas require lots of adult supervision for littles (water, rocks, etc...)
Beautiful, peaceful nature-based play areas. Great walking trails too. Fun for kids and adults.
Kids will enjoy this playground as will adults.
Beautiful location. Great walking paths, something for everyone.

properties.adr_address: 1100 Macklind Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1100 Macklind Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: HealthWorks! Kids' Museum St. Louis

reviews.text: Hello everyone to whom is reading this. The place we are talking about is something I wish I could  have had when I was a Child. This place is supper cool. I mean if you are looking for a good time and educational. This is a great place for family time. When u look at the pictures it does not do it justice and I can say enough about how great this place really is.  I know I will be letting everyone know about this place and highly recommend to everyone of all ages to come check this place out. Great work to the lady's that run this place and the employees willing to so what ever it takes to make sure the customers has a great time. Keep up the good work.

This was a pretty cool and educational visit. I have an almost three year old and she was pretty entertained by the big slide and the kitchen/foods area. I visited with several other moms and kids and a small presentation of food groups was put on by staff. Kids were asked to participate. The staff were friendly. No wow factor per say, but definitely worth a visit.
My 8 year old son has a great experience here. With added attractions this will be a very nice place to visit.

This venue was a great place for our girl scouts outing. I will definitely be booking for my child's birthday party. It's got an amazing body, a little marker, child size dentist and doctor office, they put a great show in the dental theater and the people are so polite and the environment is Beautiful and welcoming to little people.

Healthworks is a hidden gem! I didn’t know it existed until I need to kill some time after my son’s doctor appointment. It’s located across from St. Louis Community College. It has a ton of parking in the lot in front of the building. The staff is nice. Kids are free under 3 years old. $7 after they are 3 years old. Adults are $7 as well. There are so many things children can do and learn here. There is a light reaction game under the ribcage of the Giant man, there is slide that is the man’s leg. There is a doctor and dentist office, complete with the coats, and x-rays, etc. There is a market where they can shop for fruits and vegetables. My son had a blast running around! There was only two other kids there when I went on a friday afternoon at 3:30pm.

properties.formatted_address: 4746 Gravois Ave, St. Louis, MO 63116, USA
properties.name: Miniature Museum of Greater St. Louis

reviews.text:
This museum was outstanding!  Soooo much to see!  Dollhouses of all types and scales. It kind of boggles the mind, and honestly, there was so much to see that my eyes were legitimately tired when we were done.

There is a small $7/person entry fee. They do have a $1 coupon on their website.  We were only able to spend a little over an hour at the location. We could have been there at least 2 hours.

The museum includes a dollhouse store. (No entry fee to shop the store).

The only shortcomings: The museum would be hard for a person with limited mobility to explore. And I’m not sure they’d be able to access the second floor at all.  Nearly all of the displays are lighted, but a few lights didn’t work.

I bought admission from a Groupon ad. I have a small dollhouse and was interested in seeing what this place had to offer.  The experience was even better than I had imagined!  There was so much to look at & so many interesting displays.  I especially enjoyed the miniature of Bevo Mill right across the street!  They also have a gift shop where I could buy quality dollhouse items.  It’s hard to find decent furniture anywhere.  I was so thrilled that I immediately bought a membership!

This place has so many miniatures with great  details. It was great to take the time and peer in and notice all the great craftsmanship. There’s miniatures of the Old Cathedral and a wide variety of styles across two floors. It’s a hidden gem for the city.

In my husband's words, "this place is surprisingly awesome." I found it through Atlas Obscura, and with my daughter's love of all things tiny (mini brands and LOL surprise), I thought she might like checking it out. She loved it so much she is now considering a new hobby (oops).

I highly recommend a visit if you are at all interested in miniatures, museums, and detailed crafting. The ladies working there are super sweet and friendly, finding the miniature chess table with pieces my daughter HAD to have. Long after the absurdly small chess pieces are gone for good, we'll still have some pretty amazing memories and will likely make a return trip. They do have a Groupon right now, too!
Very interesting especially to see the details. Not sure how many our on display but we spent oe to 2 hours. Well worth the admission.

properties.name: The Gateway Arch

reviews.text: It's cool to see. I don't know that I'd need to do it more than once.  Buy tickets in advance. You can also check the website around 900a and see if they are any available tickets.  I checked and got a ticket for the same day.  You have to go through security as it's a national landmark.  They have a museum area after that and other setups to learn about the arch and its history, there is a gift shop and cafe inside.  Line up at your time... there aren't many people lining up until about 4-5 min prior to the scheduled time. You stand in line for a while before you get to go back. There really isn't a benefit because you get assigned a group 1 through 9. You sit with your group in the pod up and down...maximum of 5 people

Wonderful experience!  It was cool driving through town and seeing the arch get bigger and bigger as we got closer.  Then to be standing under it was amazing.  The view from the top and museum were fabulous. The tram ride was faster than expected. We’ll worth the time and Money!

Well done National Park Service! I bought tickets online about a month ahead of time. I was able to have the tickets on my phone. We arrived about 30 to 45 minutes ahead of our tour time to allow for the security check. At the appointed time we were directed through the tour. The tour guides were courteous and very helpful answering questions. The views from the top are spectacular and for me, well worth the price of admission. The ride up and down is a little bumpy and the pod is a little claustrophobic, but should be no problem for most people. There is a historical museum after entry and before or after the tour that is worth a walk through. There is a concession stand of sorts as well as a souvenir shop. Overall, a great experience!

I recently went on an adventure to St. Louis where we had the opportunity to visit the Gateway Arch. This grand stainless steel monument, completed in 1965, stands at an impressive height of 630 feet and is an iconic representation of mid-century modern design that symbolizes our national identity.
During our visit, we managed to capture some incredible shots of the arch, from the outside, the observation platform, and even from inside the underground museum. Lastly, a depiction of the tiny barrel that takes you to the top really is, which was a little amusing considering the grandeur of the arch.
The museum was a pleasant surprise, as it was filled with fascinating information on the Native Americans who were impacted by St. Louis's role in westward expansion. We were impressed with the care and polish used in the presentation of the past, which helped make it a memorable and educational experience.
Overall, our adventure to the Gateway Arch was an absolute blast. It's no wonder that it's a must-see attraction in St. Louis, and we highly recommend it to anyone.

Had a great time here with my husband, son and myself. My son and I made it to the top of the arch. The tram ride up was so unique. The top had  good views and it was quite the experience. You get about 10 minutes at the top which seemed like plenty of time. It was windy and rainy that day so we could feel the sway. The museum is so nice. And the documentary was full of great info.

reviews.text: Loved the views!! Finally got my husband to go on a Ferris wheel with me! He loved it once we got up there! You can see The Arch and many other places! Must ride at night…it’s so beautiful with the city all lit up! Must do if in the area! You won’t be disappointed!

This was a lot of fun.

It's the first ferris wheel I've encountered that has a completely enclosed compartment which makes for an interesting experience. I'm not a huge fan of heights but the views are amazing, especially at night. Overall the ride was smooth and the time just clipped by.

Definitely worth experiencing at least once!

The last night my boys were in town, I thought what better thing to do than taking them on the wheel.

We didn't get there until 8:45 that evening so a wonderful view of the lights in all directions. It was a cold evening but being this late and a cold evening we didn't encounter a line and got right in within minutes. The cab/cart/pod (whatever they are called) was warm and completely comfortable.

The views are amazing. Honestly better in the dark in my opinion.

Me and my daughter enjoyed the Wheel. Our daughter is only 21 months old and she absolutely loved it I thought maybe she would be scared when we got up really high but she ran around in the little pod. Probably the best part about it is it goes around more than just one time while you're in it it goes around like five times. Thank you so much for a amazing day.

The views were amazing! The live wasn’t long and it was a nice ride. The only downside was that I couldn’t get the air to flow on me. The tickets were per person and not per car, which I found odd. Also they take a picture of you entering, but of course you have to pay for it. It’s also a lot of other activities to do in that same area which is cool.

reviews.text: Saint Louis is my hometown but I moved away years ago, prior to this aquarium coming there. I really enjoyed my experience. The sea life was so beautiful and active during our visit. I pretty much go to an aquarium in every city I visit and this ranks pretty high with many I've seen. The cost was reasonable discounted rates for children, military/veterans, and seniors. The staff was friendly and interactive with the guest. You can even pet some variations of fish. The aquarium is what used to be the old Union Station mall and it was nice to see what they did with the space. Of course the mall was previously the  old historic train station and inside there are still original fixings from the original landmark. Plus the Amtrak train still stops there. Parking was plentiful and cost friendly as well. There were at least 15 other attractions to see there but I only had plans for the aquarium. Great family adventure.

Bought the tickets online for a 9:30am entry. Came on a weekday so it wasn't very busy and had a lot of parking. The aquarium validates parking, so I paid $5 while I was there. Did the virtual train tour, which was a great way to see a bit of history of St. Louis. There were a lot of staff there that were willing to answer questions. A lot of stations where you can pet the sea animals. There is also a large play area for kids, so I would say this place is very kid friendly. I would say it takes about an hour to an hour and half to walk through the entire aquarium while taking many pictures. I would recommend coming closer to 11 as that's when they start to feed the otters. The next feeding would be at 3pm. The otters will spend most of the time swimming around, so the feeding time would be the best to grab pictures of them.

This aquarium is smaller than some but mighty! My son loves the interactive aspects of it, the ability to touch and feel some of the wildlife, and the room to see up close. This aquarium has steps for little ones, plenty of room to view and see the fish, sharks, jellyfish, etc. so there is never a time where you can’t see. The water table, stingrays, turtles, and ability to feed and pet the animals is so incredibly cool! The staff is lovely, knowledgeable, and great with kids! Had a blast for my sons birthday!

A very nice place, love the otters and getting to see there actions as they are fed. Kind of expensive for the size of the aquarium, but I know it cost a fortune to operate an aquarium which contains these types of animals. The staff was friendly and it is a well maintained aquarium. My family had a very nice time. I highly recommend especially if you have young children. A great learning experience.

My 3 year old had a blast, but I think I might have had even more fun! Petting the sting rays was definitely a highlight for all of us! Well kept and great aquarium! I've never been to one other than the one at my local zoo in Iowa and Henry Doorly Zoo in Omaha. Thanks for a great experience. We enjoyed Union Station altogether!

reviews.text: My husband and I and our 2 teenagers did the diamond heist room while visiting St. Louis. It was a ton of fun for everyone. Even my husband, who we normally drag to these things really enjoyed it. It was just challenging enough to keep us on our toes. There was a good variety of puzzles. I definitely recommend for an entertaining and interactive experience. If you're an experienced escape room player, I would go for a more challenging room, but we enjoyed it!  Alyssa was very nice and helpful as well!

We did the Stadium Scareroom. Challenging, but definitely doable.  We did need a couple of hints, but made it out in time. Overall, well done by Mastermind and anyone who enjoys the puzzling nature of escape rooms and likes baseball would like this as well. Cannot speak to cost vs value since it was a work event and I never found out the cost per person.

Second time we've played here.  Cursed Castle is a great room.  A few puzzle mechanics we had never seen.  The room is huge, would comfortably play with 10 or even more people.  Great ambient audio.  Descent styling and theming, good, not great.

The GM was on top of it and worked hard to serve at least two rooms at the same time.  The clue system is lacking.  It appeared no one was monitoring the room full time, we had to explain what we wanted help with.  Cursed Castle is a fun room.

This was our first Escape Room with Mastermind. We were very impressed! We decided to do Diamond Heist since we had kids with us (ages 12 and 5) and didn't want anything scary. The puzzles were tricky, our Gamemaster, John, was very helpful and helped us with our 3 clues. We managed to steal the diamond in time! We will definitely be back for another room!
My husband and I did the Elf Escape room with our 4 kids ages 19-26. We had a great time working together! We will definitely go back.

reviews.text: Jacob was so fun and made the experience very enjoyable! Will definitely come back and ask for him on another room! He is very personable and funny!

Jacob was a fabulous guide!  He helped our family make it out of the Western Bank Heist after fumbling around quite a bit. It was hilarious my husband and I and are 7 and 9 year old children trying to “rob a bank” and escape. The puzzle and clues were challenging and so fun! Would highly recommend to anyone that is looking for family fun or fun with friends. We already started talking about the next one we want to do. Thanks Jacob! We will be back!
Zero was very helpful! We had a blast (and not just because we used dynamite). We’ll be back next time we need some money

This location is amazing! Our game master was Jacob and he gave us a great theatrical and comforting experience, so well we booked another room after completing our original room. I’ve played many escape rooms across the country and this location will be remembered by far. His Customer service was genuinely unmatched. Way to go Jacob

The bank robbery room was fun and challenging! Krista was a great clue master. My only complaint would be that you had to share the room with other people. So working on a big puzzle with strangers was awkward and at times frustrating. Otherwise super fun!

reviews.text: As a motorcycle enthusiast, I absolutely loved this museum. There's a wonderful variety of motorcycles from all throughout the 20th and 21st centuries from several countries. The founder and collector, Mr. Steve Smith, did a great job with this facility and I enjoyed the information on the placards explaining the history of the bike and story of how Mr. Smith acquired the bike.

We had our wedding here. Best decision we made! From our first tour, we were sold. Not only was the space cool and unique, the event team was by far the best, most personable and most accommodating we met. Our coordinator Steve sealed the deal and made our event perfect! Anything we asked, he was accommodating to. Colleen was also fabulous, couldn't have asked for a better team. Day of, our wedding was amazing, to see how they transformed the space was breathtaking, they truly brought my (our) vision to life. While the space is obviously filled with motorcycles, it's amazing how they were able to transform the space to make it what we wanted. Everyone raved about the food and the event staff made sure everything was perfect and attended to all our needs the night of...no matter the request. Seriously would recommend this space and team to anyone
Loved the primarily pre-1975 European motorcycle collection! Worth a visit especially since the museum is free.
This is well worth a visit, especially if you  love vintage, rare motorcycles.

Finally got the Bluetooth module installed on my Triumph Speed Triple and Moto Europa was awesome about getting the software update done. Great shop! Thank you for sharing the info about the update and how it's done.

reviews.text: This venue is great all around.   They have good sets and the puzzles are nice and align well with each story.   The puzzles do have a tendency to be quite similar, but that can be overlooked.   It gets quite busy over the weekend, so be sure to book the rooms early.

These escape rooms are always so so so much fun! Unique set ups, and themes for the room with just the right amount of challenge! You'll have a blast with these. I also really like the fact that they offer put put golf as well. It's kind of expensive but it is fun for the whole family. The glow in the dark set up puts a unique spin on it as well.

So amazing. The only negative is the stairs, we didn't know about it being a 2nd story but we made it. The "room host" I forget what she called herself, but she was fantastic. She made our experience so much better. Would definitely come back and try out another room!

We had an amazing time in an immersive room! The puzzles were hard but so much fun! Afterwards we played the funnest mini golf I’ve ever played. 100% coming back with a group to tackle more scary rooms!

Love the glow in the dark mini golf! All of the “holes” are unique and we just played for fun but you can keep score if you want. It took about an hour for us to go through. This is the second time we’ve been (last time was 2 years ago) and there is new “holes” added and some familiar ones so that’s nice they update them from time to time.

Complaint:
I will say it’s definitely not accesible to get to unless there’s a secret elevator somewhere that I don’t know about. There’s a very steep set of stairs that you have to walk up to get to the escape rooms, mini golf, and arcade. (I was very out of breath lol) It seems like this is built in an old warehouse of some kind so that might explain the strange stairs? But yeah… there’s no way for someone with a wheel chair or other physical disability to get up there unfortunately :/

reviews.text: My family visited for the first time as we were in town for vacation. We got there late so we got to enjoy the reduced pricing. My 9 and 11 year olds had a good time. There was plenty to do and everything is wheelchair accessible. Staff was friendly.

Cute little area for kids who like to be expressive.  Several different areas to explore including legos, clay, art, building, Cricut, and 3D printing.

Pros:
- Price: $5per ticket (everyone including adults pay to enter).  After 3pm price goes does to $3
- Lots to explore, if kids like expressive type activities you could easily spend the afternoon here
- Parking is free.
- There was a pottery demonstration when we were there.

Cons:
- Not an ideal location, parking was across very busy road.
- Many activities came at an additional cost.  Pottery painting, Cricut activities, 3D printing.
- Very small location, gets very loud, not ideal for kids with sensory issues

This place is awesome! The staff is helpful and there is so much to do.  With our 5 kiddos we thought we'd run out of things to do really quickly but we were dead wrong.  We had to drag our kids out of there they loved it so much.  Military discount goes a long way here.  Great people! Great place!
My 8yr old  Loves this place! He is a tech kids and love to create things, I love making things with the clay because you get to keep it! Every you have to pay for is only $5!! Its really amazing!!
The kids (and parents) loved this! There is so much to do and the stations are incredibly well thought out. There is something to do and entertain (while also leaning) for all ages.

reviews.text: An amazing National Park, much smaller than most parks but still has plenty to offer. If you are here to get to the top of the arch then you are in for a good time. The whole experience if fantastic and the top has some great views. Underneath the arch there is a great museum and plenty of historical artifacts. The park itself is also amazing, has plenty of trees and walking areas. There is a riverfront and pond to walk near as well. Quiet and peaceful overall.

What a wonderful experience it was. When we decided to come to see the arch we had know idea what to expect. Absolutely breath taking and the history and meaning behind it is just inspiring. It was a great day from the arrival in the city until we left. This whole experience is something I never imagined and the views from the arch are stunning. After the tour we went to the movie and the museum and it was all fascinating. What a great place and a must see for everyone.

This was the favorite attraction on our visit to St Louis. We reserved our tram tickets well in advance online. We got to the museum, got in line and only had to wait about 10 minutes for our tour to start. Our group was small and because of covid you currently get to ride in the pods with just your party which was nice as they are super tiny and would be no fun with strangers. The views from the top are amazing. Plenty of time to take pictures in the 8 minutes you get up there. We were on the North tram. The group that came up from the south tram was much larger so it's all luck of the draw. A smaller group with a nice for us because you can choose any of the windows to look out of on the top without being crowded. Each pod has a window for a door so you can see the inner workings of the arch which we thought was super cool! Everyone was super friendly. We got drinks and the huge pretzel from the cafe. Very expensive for a pretzel and drinks. Parking was only $9 in the East stadium lot for 5 hours which is only a couple blocks away and an easy walk. Plenty of time to look through the nicely done Museum, do the tram ride to the top, eat something at the cafe, and explore a neighboring Park!

The only word that comes to mind to describe the Gateway Arch National Park is "Indescribable!"  The history of the territory and architecture of the arch, the panoramic view of Missouri and of the Mississippi are indescribably awesome!  The museum is easy to tour, the movie is a must see, and the riverboat ride is an excellent touch.  The staff is extremely helpful and professional.  Do be prepared for federal government style security checks when entering the park.  Tour pricing is based upon what attractions you want to see and scheduling is set to accommodate your arrival and departure time frames.

What a fun place to visit! It may be the smallest
National Park, but they pack a lot in this area. The museum was incredibly informative and I learned a lot. The tram ride to the top was thrilling. It offered one-of-a-kind views of the city and would recommend to anyone. Well the tram may be small, the ride went by very quick. I would recommend a pair of headphones to help distract you if you are claustrophobic. The museum staff and park rangers answered every question I had and even offered some additional advice. When I went, the old courthouse was still being renovated and was closed.

Here. This is the riverfront area to see the most famous arch. We drove here in the night to see the mighty Mississippi River, the bridges and the arch on the bank. We parked our car in the street for a while and took a small walk. It was chilly night, so couldn’t walk more. I’m sure it will be great in the summer evenings. The arch looks great as a monument, although we visited the gateway arch on the next day and took the tram ride to the top. This riverfront is a nice place with a quaint charm.

***A MUST SEE***
Excellent experience and adventure at the Riverfront, the Museum and (of course) the Gateway Arch.

Hello St Louis! The Gateway Arch is gorgeous and shimmers in the sunlight. It is also known as the Gateway to the Midwest.
If you want to go up into the arch, you must buy tickets in advance; however, you can buy SAME DAY tickets with a variety of times to choose from. I did not know about the same day tickets so I was bummed that I missed my chance because I didn't have enough time before I had to leave.
Google Maps did not let me down to get me there due to the construction. Other reviews said not to follow Google Maps but I did not have any issues.
The riverfront was great. The parking was the only downside. The parking was on brick that was jagged and at an angle. There are no set ways to park. Just find a spot and walk away.
They had two food trucks. Yay!

After suffering a huge headache from the arch, this was a good idea to relax and unwind. You get to see the city and learn something about the architecture.
Too many people were on the boat. The seats were small and uncomfortable. There was no leg room since seats are close to each other.
Make sure to get decent seats on top for better view.

reviews.text: I always like visit Federal Reserve Bank museum in other States. Free to come. Recommended and buy some souvenirs from FRB gift shop inside. Don’t forget to visit this place when you’re in St Louis area.
Awesome interactive place. So many great videos and things for kids to do. Totally worth stopping in for a couple hours. Even free souvenirs at the end.
Interesting.... I had to wear a mask because I didn't have my updated vaccine booster information. Not a big deal.

Adults had to show photo ID (currently no mask/vaccine requirements) and the check in process  took a few minutes. The museum was great! Content seems aimed at teenage learners but there was more than enough for our 9 year old to interact with.  It was a valuable learning experience presented in a way that really stuck with him.

No longer need proof of vaccination or masks. We visited the Economy Museum without many expectations but my sons (14, 11, 8) all really enjoyed the experience. Many interactive exhibits and an area to try your hand at trading on the stock market. We had the opportunity to try and lift a gold brick, learn about and see ancient currency, identify fake currency, and view the currency of many other countries. My husband was impressed with the relevancy of the information and how up to date the information was. A bonus is the bag of shredded cash all guests are allowed to take. Overall, a nice experience. Middle school and up is the target audience but there was plenty of stuff to keep the 8 year old entertained. Worth a visit! Spent about 1.5 hours there.

We love checking out local parks while walking our little Doodle Dog. One of our favorites is Francis Park in the lovely Saint Louis Hills neighborhood. The view is out of the world.  You also get to learn the history how the Gateway Arch (Gateway to the West) was made in the Tucker Theater which is an inspiring story in itself.

reviews.text:
The Kiener plaza is a small park offering great views of the Old Courthouse and the gateway arch, a real treasure in the city centre.

Kiener Plaza is like a town square for the city of St. Louis. New buildings overlooking the ballpark and the historic Old Courthouse (which has museum exhibit rooms) frame the park. Also the Wainwright Building is on its west side. This building, designed by Louis Sullivan, is considered to be the first steel-frame office building, built in the 1800s. Kiener himself is memorialized by a statue titled "The Runner". He was an athlete at the 1904 St. Louis Olympic Games. I always park on the street nearby, and it is within walking distance of the Gateway Arch. For children, there are structures that are fun to climb on.

The park itself is a nice go-to place for a casual visit, sit down and sip coffee, have the little ones play in the kids area, or ice skating during the winters. What makes it more special is that during holidays time (Christmas), it’s lit up so nice with a tree, and lights, surrounded by warm igloos where you can go rest in between, and also there’s a coffee truck that has few good options. A must visit place for a casual and relaxed evening during Christmas.

I really liked the park... So green and clean and the weather was still kind of cold even by end of May. The strange thing with the park was that it had a curfew between 8 pm-10 pm, which really made me feel uncomfortable walking around. You couldn't find people walking around there even earlier than that...
It's a beautiful  place to visit when you're in Downtown St.louis. Unfortunately, St.louis Downtown is a high crime area. Don't leave your valuable belongings in the car.
Its a nice spot.. not crowded at all when I went. Great view of the old Courthouse, arch and fountain  ⛲️

reviews.text: I can’t wait to come back and try a boat ride. But the food!! So Good. I had the smoked salmon sandwich. This was a flavorful decent size salmon on croissant. The cucumbers in the cucumber salad were fresh and crisp. The tiramisu cake…was so spongy and delicious.

My wife and I went there for brunch after  attending Easter Services. We were not disappointed. The food and the service were first rate. The brunch menu was varied and delicious. It was a cool day but the food was kept warm. I chose to get lemonade but it was not available at that time. One of the staff on duty got the drink set up and brought it to our table.

There were several desserts available as well. The cookies and cakes were tasty.  We brought some treats home. The staff encouraged us to take home what we wanted. They were quite nice and added to our experience.  Just before we left, one of the staff gave us food to feed the ducks that were on the lake.

The Boathouse will have a Mother's Day brunch on that special Sunday. The food, if it will like today's, will be worth the price.  It definitely was today. I suspect it is everyday it is open. We will go back in the future.

It is still popular weeks later. On a Sunday afternoon in June there was a long line outside to order afternoon lunch. Of course there was no table service on that day. That played a role. Still it is a great place to eat.

The Boathouse at Forest Park is one of those places that makes you love living in St. Louis.    Located across from the World’s Fair Pavilion, the Boathouse is a casual, fun place to hangout.  Many times they have live music, kids can feed the ducks, and dogs are welcome.  If you feel like going out on the water there are kayaks and paddle boats that you can rent.  I also love bringing my guests from out of town here.

Delicious foods as always courtesy to SugarFire ❤️😋😃 and a nice ambiance, never tired to visit this place  yesterday (3-25-23) the time we're there having a good meals while enjoying the nice weather, which their costumers listening to a good band.🤗🥰🙏
We had the most wonderful lunch here. The food is surprisingly good and the live music was fantastic. Plus, what a view. Can't recommend enough.

properties.adr_address: 1508 Locust St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Restored 19th-century home displaying period furnishings, paintings & the family's personal effects.

properties.formatted_address: 1508 Locust St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: Campbell House Museum

reviews.text: Beautiful Victorian Home. Tour Guide Ginger was an amazing historian of the home and have a wonderfully nice personality. The home is well kept and clean, very much worth $10 dollars per person. Our tour last around an hour long as well. I contributed $50 to keep the home in tip top shape.
Great little museum preserving a little chapter of St Louis history.  An Intern gave the tour and did a good job

Lovely restored and preserved Victorian home! Honestly the most beautiful historic home I've toured. Our tour guide was very knowledgeable and presented in details about the house! A must see in st Louis!!

This is an unbelievable experience. The house, story, and furnishings are all restored and so unique. If visiting St. Louis, this should be a top attraction, along with the Arch, Zoo, Soulard, Lafayette Square, Forest Park, and Anheuser Busch Brewery. The tour is very reasonably priced and worth every penny.

This tour gave us a true picture of a Victorian home, ESPECIALLY since everything in the house is original AND there are so many well-preserved photos!
Dennis, our docent is both passionate & extremely knowledgeable about all aspects of the property.

properties.adr_address: 5050 Oakland Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Planetarium at the St. Louis Science Center since 1963, with live star shows & interactive exhibits.

properties.formatted_address: 5050 Oakland Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Saint Louis Science Center

reviews.text: The science center is a wonderful experience! Our 5 year old had a fantastic time. There are three floors of exhibits as well as two gift shops,  a theater, planetarium, and small area for concessions. General admission is free but the shows, planetarium, and some other things do cost, as well as parking is $10 if you're not a member. We visited on a Saturday morning. There was no wait to get in, nor to buy tickets to anything, but the whole place was quite busy. Overall, we had a great time and would recommend visiting.

Pretty neat place for you to bring your family. It's a great place to learn about science and see how some common things work. It's free to enter, but some attractions require you to purchase tickets. There's free street parking if you're willing to walk a couple minutes. You can also park at forest park and walk through from the planetarium side.

Another great, free gem for our city. So many exhibits and areas to explore. Throughout the many floors, you can learn about all things science! There are Hands-On activities and artifacts as well as demonstrations and shows. It's a great place to spend the day with kids of all ages. There are other activities for additional cost such as toddler areas, educational movies and interactive exhibits. The video game exhibit on the bottom floor was a little lacking since there were many things that were out of service. The kids always love exploring the dinosaur area and seeing some fossils and geological finds from our area is always cool. We usually park over at the planetarium and walk across the bridge to view the cars driving below but the parking lot has been closed for some time. Unfortunately, the only other parking besides street parking which is 3 hours, is the science Center lot which costs $12. If you purchase a movie ticket you only pay $6 for parking. They offer military discount for service members on several paid offerings. There are concessions and drinking fountains throughout. We really enjoyed the vault area which can be found on the planetarium side of the bridge. Definitely check it out if you're in the St Louis area. We are grateful for this great addition to the city!

Amazing place for you to explore the wonders of science . Visited this with a 6 years and 10 years old, they absolutely loved it. Would definitely recommend this place. The planetarium entrance is closed. So you will have to either find street side parking or pay and park in the science center parking lot , which costs around $12.  The paid parking lot has many fuel efficient parking spaces and 2 electric car charging station.

We had so much fun at the St. Louis Science Center. It’s probably the best science center I’ve ever been to and it’s awesome that it’s free. We will definitely go again. I only expected to spend maybe 2 hours but we spent 3 and only left then because we had other reservations. You could easily spend 4+ hours. The video game display could use a little attention though many of those items did not work as intended.

properties.adr_address: 20 N 4th St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.formatted_address: 20 N 4th St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Luther Ely Smith Park

reviews.text:
***A MUST SEE***
Excellent experience and adventure that began at Luther Ely Smith Park!  From there we toured the Museum at the Gateway Arch. We bought the movie and the ride to the top.
Price was good.
Lines were short.
Staff was friendly.
Food was decent.
Museum history was fantastic!
Artifacts were captivating.
Movie was worth it!
Ride to the top was awesome!
Views were breathtaking!
Outside grounds were clean.
Inside was tidy.

If you've never been here - don't skip it. Go!  I've been through St. Louis many times but never stopped to explore. So glad that I did.

Enjoy the pics and hit the HELPFUL button.

Thanks,
BRIAN HARGIS

A great open space to view the Gateway Arch from a short distance.  This really adds perspective to the scope of the arch.

Lush grass to enjoy and plenty of space to run around.
What a amazing place to walk around at night especially. A beautiful park that goes down the middle of St. Louis very peaceful and clean. A hidden Gem for sure.
It's so much fun there. So many nice things to see and water fountains for kids to play with them
Beautiful place to visit along with the Old Courthouse and Gateway Arch!

properties.adr_address: 999 N 2nd St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.formatted_address: 999 N 2nd St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: St. Louis Fun Tours

reviews.text: Great way to start your trip to St Louis if you are not familiar with the city. The driver was friendly & knowledgeable about the area and gave great details about the city and activities. Definitely would recommend.
I loved the tour. I recommend coming here as your first stop so you can check out st louis and get a list of museums and restaurants you want to visit.

Free parking at the Lumiere Hotel/Horseshoe casino was nice and tour guide Larry was into his job. I suggest saving your money- over priced for what it is. I regretted spending that much once I had done it. Go see Forest Park and the Arch in person.

100% recommend. Larry, the driver/tour guide, was absolutely fantastic. Tour started as advertised, covered all the bases, but he kept it light and fun with witty/ dad jokes throughout the tour. Was a great way to see a lot of the city and learn the layout while taking it in.
Larry  was be a great guide. Funny and knowledgeable. Made some stops along the be way at different places that we could go inside of. Great tour and price.

properties.adr_address: 720 N 2nd St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Life-size wax replicas of famous figures, real & fictional, in a circa-1885 former warehouse.

properties.formatted_address: 720 N 2nd St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Laclede's Landing Wax Museum

reviews.text: This wax museum was so much fun. I won't lie to you and say every single wax figure was believable and lifelike. But I will say that walking through identifying them was a total blast. If you happened to go and did not check out the horror section, you'd absolutely be missing out. It's not a haunted house, but I'd say it's better than one. No, nothing touches you or reaches out, but it's so creepy and weird that it seriously terrified me. I'd recommend this to anyone looking for a fun thing to do that's off the beaten path.

Very good wax museum especially the horror part my only complaint is that alot of the animatronics (Ghostface Freddy Kreuger Regan) are completely broken i definitely think they could use a bit of repair and could use a little bit of light
Very cheesy and sub-par, but that's exactly why I loved every bit of it! It was so much fun. Basement is NOT for kids.

I'm sorry, but this place is weirdly wonderful! If you're looking for Madam Tussauds than you'll be disappointed, but if you're looking for the odd and unusual (which I prefer) than look no more! I have been coming here for 25 years and it always leaves a lasting impression!

Bring a flashlight. some of the exhibits are very dark and you are unable to see what they are. Most of the Statues are very dusty. The museum is very cool and worth the visit. For $10 for adults its worth the visit.

properties.adr_address: 806 Cliff Cave Rd, St. Louis, MO 63129, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Long limestone formation gated to protect bats, with natural grounds & river for picnics & hiking.

properties.formatted_address: 806 Cliff Cave Rd, St. Louis, MO 63129, USA
properties.name: Cliff Cave County Park

reviews.text: Such a beautiful park along the Mississippi! Full of off beaten trails with obstacles to hike that lead to streams, bluffs, the infamous cave, and so much more. Great for exploring or going on a leisurely stroll with friends and family.

This is a beautiful place to go hiking with well maintained concrete and dirt trails with amazing bike trails too! This park has a cave on the lower part of the hill across from the bridge. I'd recommend going down to see it if you can
Peaceful and Beautiful! A lovely place to walk and see Nature's Beauty! Many different birds singing, Deer throughout the trail. Wild Flowers and wonderful scenery!

(Febuary 26, 2022) I went on the day after my birthday to celebrate with a friend. Had such an amazing time, so beautiful and great memories were made. Fun time for a walk and seeing some beautiful scenery.
What a beautiful place to go. The paved trail makes it easy for all ages. I'll have to bring my puppy back here.

properties.adr_address: 1525 S 8th St, St. Louis, MO 63104-3811, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1525 S 8th St, St. Louis, MO 63104, USA
properties.name: The Darkness Haunted House

reviews.text: My first time visiting The Darkness was really fun and worth the money! The line was short the night we went, we absolutely loved the actors standing in line (especially the actor who was “proposing” to people with the finger ring—he did a fantastic job!), and my mom and I were truly scared inside the haunted house, especially of the actors jumping out and scaring you and not knowing when to expect them. At the end, there are lots of cool photo opportunities and a cool shop to buy memorabilia and scary stuff. I would absolutely return again next year when they’ve changed it a bit and for the seasonal events!

Best Haunted House experience I’ve had. Many scenes from many different horror movies. Lot’s of money put into their props. Well worth the ticket price. I’d suggest paying for the speed pass. The lines are over a block long without it. Definitely planning a return trip! Horror fanatics will love it!😎😍 BRAVO! GREAT PERFORMANCE to the actors 👏

Always a scary time at The Darkness. Although there is always a line, the staff is very organized and the lines move rapidly. This is one of the best IF not the best haunted house I've been to in this area. The actor portrayal is always great. Guaranteed a scary fun time.

Fun way to spend an evening.  It was fun once but I doubt if they get too much repeat business. Be sure and pay the extra ten dollar to get a timed entry as the lines for general admission were pretty long.

Loved the animatronics. Definitely a lot of time and money spent in this awesome horror house. Although I have two things I didn’t like. The parking on the street which was free, was all packed filled I ended up having to pay to park in the “conveniently” placed parking area right in front of the building. The second and most important thing, we were only able to stay for 30 minutes walking through the house. On the darkness website it says to take your time. But when they let new people in every two or three minutes, you can’t really stop and get a look at anything. Even letting people by me so I can walk instead of fast paced like them, within a minute I had another group of people rushing me. I bought some awesome stuff at the store at the end and took some awesome pictures. Next year I’ll be trying creepyworld, I know just as much effort is put into creepyworld… and maybe it being more spread out I won’t be rushed. There were also people smoking in line which usually doesn’t bother me but people were shoulder to shoulder. And there was a few couples extremely intoxicated behind me, and they were let into the house which made it really annoying.

properties.formatted_address: St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Jewel Box

reviews.text: Great space for an event with all the plants hanging about. There are bathrooms in the back and down the stairs. The history of the place is also really cool as it dates back to 1916! It does cost $1 to walk around the place on a normal day but it’s worth it. The lily pond out front is also fun to walk around. The grounds are kept up beautifully.

The Jewel Box in Forest Park is a lovely horticultural greenhouse with lovely displays throughout the year. They are open:
Monday through Thursday, from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m.
Friday from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m.
Saturday, from 9 to 11 a.m.
Sunday, from 9 a.m. to 2 p.m
Admission is $1 per person, but it is free on Monday and Tuesday from 9 a.m. until noon.

A lovely treat inside and out, especially in late Spring and summer when the lily pond is active and the outdoor flowers are bursting in bloom!

A Saint Louis treat in beautiful Forest Park.
Beautiful - Tulips are in bloom now and are a must see.  Have been to a wedding here and it was amazing.

I had my wedding here on February 4, 2023 and it was perfect. I got so many compliments on the venue. The man working on the night of my rehearsal was very kind and knowledgeable when I had questions. The doors were even open early for both my rehearsal and wedding, and that was so appreciated with it being chilly outside. I would 100% recommend having your wedding ceremony at the Jewel Box.

The entrance is gorgeous. So many beautiful flowers blooming during the summer. Wonderful place to take family and friends. A lot of benches to rest at while looking at the flowers. The inside is even more beautiful. It is open year round and all week long. Overall a great experience.

properties.adr_address: 13219 Streetcar Dr, Maryland Heights, MO 63043, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Adventure-activity chain venue where groups explore the forest canopy via a treetop rope course.

properties.formatted_address: 13219 Streetcar Dr, Maryland Heights, MO 63043, USA
properties.name: Go Ape Zipline and Adventure Park

reviews.text: Great customer service. We made some great memories while doing this course and plan to go back. It looked small when we walked around it but it was not, it was perfect.

Great adventure for the family. The adult experience was varied and more physically challenging than what I expected. Most extreme routes also have "easier" alternative routes. Gloves are required. The price is high but I would say it's definitely worth it. Priceless experience shared with those I care most about before they head off to college.

What an AMAZING staff and experience. I had a non neuro typical kiddo with me and they went out of their way to instill confidence in him. They spent the time to help him and answer all of his questions. By the time we made it up, he had no fear and felt so well prepared! I am so very happy that he was able to experience this and complete not 1 but 2 courses!!

What a genius idea, great fun and challenging!  I took my husband and kids for father's day.   We had a blast and they had fun challenging and supporting ME!  You see,  I haven't done this before.  It was better than I thought I could do!   There are 5 courses and zip lines.  You go up as high as 70 feet, maybe more.  The training you get to do this is thorough and the staff is around if you need them!  I was tired by the end, but what an excellent way to spend quality time with family and have fun at the same time!
We always enjoy doing this!!!! It's a great exercise 👍🏻 Thank you Morgan 😎 for being an awesome instructor!!!! Watch for those baby deer ❤️

properties.adr_address: 50 S Leonor K Sullivan Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Depot for traditional Mississippi paddleboat tours past the iconic 63-storey Gateway Arch.

properties.formatted_address: 50 S Leonor K Sullivan Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Gateway Arch Riverboats

reviews.text:
Best pricing around, except for the second half of the tour, because the taxes are higher on the Illinois side. During the tour you will see something for the record books.  Not the FIRST largest, or the SECOND largest, but the THIRD largest cable bridge in the United States! There is creative urban artwork to see for the duration of the tour. There is more than one fact to learn about the area.  You will get questions answered that you did not even know you wanted to ask, like how many tours are done per day based on the season. Thanks to the nearby homeless community, your belongings will always be watched.  Get your picture taken in front of the arch, while you look at the real thing! The tables sway with the boat, even when the boat is not swaying.  Learn about the three historically significant things that happened in St Louis.  Admire the sparkling brown water.  When the fish are active, they cannot be seen.  Parking is readily available, expensive, and great for people that do not worry about the suspension in their vehicles.  If you have a rollover warning, beware!
Shoe choice is important, don't trip on the brick, stilettos not recommended.  Want to spend 75% of the tour standing in line to eat? The snack bar is recommended, BUT make sure to purchase before the tour gets to the Illinois side, so you don't spend more on taxes.

We had a beautiful sightseeing tour aboard the famed Tom Sawyer! Learned a lot while floating down the river! Great setting for taking pics and a  great way to just kick back and relax for a bit!! Would definitely recommend to anyone!

We had a combo ticket with the “Arch”.  There is a parking lot in front of the riverboat. They
have two decks to choose from. You can get food on the riverboat. You can have a small group.
They talk about the history of the river. They take you on a one-hour river-boat tour.

Nice fun driver who taught about historic places and bridges, smelled fishy on the ride though...no pun intended. Boat was VERY smooth and only ever felt it slightly tilt maybe an inch or 2 from a bigger wave. Indoor and outdoor seating with amazing views of the gateway arch! (picture of gateway arch from boat)

Took my daughter on the Skyline Dinner Cruise for a date.  We had a wonderful time!  The food was pretty good.  We enjoyed the musicians.  Our waitress was very friendly and did a great job.  It was a bit pricey.  I tried to think of it as most of the money going for the ticket/experience, and only a smaller portion going for the actual meal.  And that's fine, because sitting on the top deck after dinner while watching the downtown skyline go by was the highlight of the evening, anyway.

Also note, if you have a child young enough to qualify as a child, but they want a regular meal and not a kids meal, you will pay the adult price.  The website seems to indicate that the price is based on age, but it's really based on what type of meal you order.

properties.formatted_address: 3100 S Jefferson Ave, St. Louis, MO 63118, USA
