reviews.text: This is such a beautiful, peaceful, and happy park with trails and two ponds, plus plenty of wildlife! So cool!! They have enough to keep the family busy and smiling all the way here's tennis courts, walking/bicycling trails, a playground for the kids. The entire park is very scenic with it's rolling hills and wildlife to keep you entertained for hours.

This is always been a nice park to go to on the hill. When my older brother and I were kids we used to have sporting events on our local St Louis athletic club team and we would play soccer or baseball or whatever sport was going on for that time of year. The only reason I don't give it five stars is because it's kind of tiny. If it was just a tad bigger maybe double in size, then it would be the perfect place for any southsider that resides anywhere close to the hill
Our neighborhood park - beautiful, peaceful, nice people, free concerts, great atmosphere, perfect for dogs!

Benton Park is great!  We feed the ducks and the pair of geese as they are the cutest creatures in the area.  There are fish too although they’re abit timid. Lovely park to walk around with your dog and even has a nice a nice bridge.   Supposedly there are caves underneath.  I’ve seen a map but haven’t physically looked.  Anyway, the old homes surrounding the park and the park itself with the lovely wildlife is a nice retreat from the laptop eyes I have.
Its a big park so u got enough room for alot of people. It could be kinda updated but it's still nice.

properties.formatted_address: 710 N 2nd St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Laclede's Landing Neighborhood Association

reviews.text: Really picturesque with the red brick buildings, cobblestone streets and landscaping 🧱💐 It may not have as many restaurants as it used to, but it's still a nice place to visit. Very convenient location and less than a block from a metro station.

Most of the restaurants and shops are gone due to Covid. The area itself isn’t living up to its full potential, with vacant areas and a lack of development. Nothing really to see besides a different view of the arch. Would not go out of your way to visit until they take care of the area.

The Landing is still worth a visit, but it's just not what is was in the 80s & early 90s.
I think the clean-up & re-furbish of Washington Street kinda upstaged the Landing.
Great place to help the less fortunate and meet good people that have fallen on hard times
Always have loved the landing area, historic with sweet shops and little restaurants all over, very close to metro right by the arch and river.

properties.formatted_address: 185 W Trendley Ave, East St Louis, IL 62201, USA
properties.name: Mississippi River Overlook

plus_code.compound_code: JRCF+XR East St. Louis, IL, USA

reviews.text: This is a great way to see the St. Louis Arch. There is a ramp that goes up 3 levels to get a birdseye view of St. Louis.  Also up there is a statue of Malcolm Martin who had a hand in helping develop Memorial Park which encompasses both sides of the river. There is a webcam as well so family and friends back home can log on and see you live looking at the arch. You also get a view of the bridges too.  Plenty of parking. There was only one other person there when I was there on a Thursday afternoon.  I can only imagine the sunsets are amazing from this point of view.

I love taking pictures of different city skylines. So this looked like the best place to do that. Unfortunately like others mentioned there are many obstructions like wires and some other things. It doesn't make for the perfect picture. However, it is still a good view. Very well kept park. I spent about 2 hours here waiting for the sun to set and only one other person came to the park. Not sure if I just picked a good day or if it's usually like that. I'd reccomend a visit here.
Nice view of the city and the arch.  Would be a bit nicer if the view wasn’t obstructed by industrial and train activity.  Could use some barbecue pits, picnic shelters and communal showers.

Very nice view from across the river. I really thought the camera available for live viewing was pretty neat. I had my mother-in-law go online to view the camera while we waved. She did mention it was a bit delayed but she finally saw us. It tickled me to think she could see us since we don't get to see her often. It was a good walk up though.
The daily geyser at noon for 15 minutes on a calm day can get up to 600 feet with 6 smaller geysers around it. Great wheelchair accessible overlook to the Arch.

Thank You Whittaker Foundation...Grace Hill, Affinnia and other sponsors..
I like tht park they do  free concerts in the summer and it be live music and all types of snacks and drinks for sell just a great time and space to get together and enjoy your community

The city Forest department should be a shame of themselves. The grass was cut at! You couldn't really see the sidewalk because the tremors refuse to get the grass off the sidewalk. They were even too lazy to blow the grass so that you can walk on the sidewalk.
So long as the kids can play on peace, its an idea place.

Great family atmosphere been that way for years

I love Terry Park! It's within walking distance to my residence!
I take a shortcut through park when going down Compton

This is a park where I grew up we had such much fun there its like a neighborhood place for ppl that use to live in the area still come out and hang out and so good things like Mother's/ Father's  day, Back to school events  n more

The playground was fun for my daughter. There were two separate playground units: one for younger and one for older kids. There was a swing set, as well, but only two regular swings and two child swings. The one big drawback was that the playground area itself was filthy. There was trash everywhere and no trashcans to throw it away.

properties.adr_address: 700 Clark Ave, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Home of MLB’s St. Louis Cardinals, this red-brick ballpark offers tours & Gateway Arch views.

properties.formatted_address: 700 Clark Ave, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Busch Stadium

reviews.text: Took a tour of one of the most beautiful stadiums I've ever been to.  Our tour guide gave us some great historical facts.  Even though the Cardinals aren't my team, I gained a new perspective of the city and their team (11 championships).  At almost 20 years old, the stadium still looks brand new.  The grounds keepers keep the grass and dirt looking perfectly amazing.  Seeing the Gateway Arch in the background is even more awe inspiring.  The tour allows you to actually sit in the dugout and see what it's like being so close to the field itself.  Take the tour.  You won't be disappointed.  In addition, walking on the street, you are so close to the excitement of the game.  It's as if the restaurants and streets are inside the stadium, even though they're right outside.  It is the only stadium I've seen that incorporates and envelops the outside streets at the same level.  Fun place to visit.  Can't wait to actually see a game there.

One of the most beautiful stadiums in baseball! Love the red brick & black wrought iron retro look. Cardinal fans are some of the best in baseball. Electric atmosphere. Rich history. You won't be disappointed! 5 out 5 stars!

Top-5 stadium in baseball to catch a game. It truly is baseball heaven as you take in the smells and ambiance of the park and of course St. Louis Cardinals baseball. The view of the Gateway Arch is immaculate. However, be aware of the Gestapo patrolling the entry gates. Some Cardinals ushers take their job a little too seriously, so make sure you read what is and isn't allowed in the stadium before you have to make a jaunt back to your car. Lots of reasonable parking lots around the radius of the stadium. The concession stands and souvenir shops are second to none. If you arrive early their is plenty to do in and around the stadium (Ballpark Village and Jefferson Expansion National Park). Put Busch Stadium on your bucket list, it's a good one.

Top 5 of the best stadiums I've been to. The only thing that you need to do is educate your employees on where the same day memorabilia is in the park. It took me a better part of two innings to find because no one could direct me. But I will be back. I did enjoy the experience there and the seats are all wonderful. I also suggest doing the stadium tour before the game.

I'm not a Cardinal's fan, but they have a great stadium!  Busch Stadium is clean and family friendly.  We had seats in section 365 and we had a great view.  There is a lot going on around the stadium pregame, so get there early and take in some extra fun.  Enjoy the game!

properties.adr_address: 3750 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Venerable institution featuring modern art exhibits, as well as related educational programs.

properties.formatted_address: 3750 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.name: Contemporary Art Museum St. Louis

reviews.text: A vibrant midtown museum with rotating exhibition of amazing artists from world over. It’s all free and ample parking available around the building. The large space with some video- audio displays are very interesting touch. A small cafe with a nice outdoor space to have a cup of cappuccino!

Saint Louis is a city that.is lucky to have such a vibrant arts scene, and one of the crowning jewels.is the Contemporary Art Museum.  Tucked away in Grand Center, the CAM is FREE to all guests and provides several galleries of cutting-edge, thoughtful, and thought-provoking work.  Stop by often and immerse yourself in their exhibits and then come back again to find something new.

Didn’t know what to expect coming here. Museum is free. Upstairs they have art from High school kids talking about equity & equality. Downstairs there’s more adult art from when we visited. Very abstract, thought provoking, graphic. Don’t bring kids to the downstairs there is nudity. Very fun place.

Profetic 2nd floor installment done to promote artwork for equity was magnificent beyond words. Its shine was diminished due to the main exhibitions cacophony of insanity.

For better accessibility and immersion in various experiences, a start and stop button per video station would have allowed people to start the videos' Journey at any time. Unless it was the artist intent to overwhelm people with sensory issues, glad I brought my headphones, I believe they would like their art respected as individual pieces instead of Orchestra of Madness.

Sustainability and energy wise? I would be curious to know their data on how many people visit throughout the week. I was there most of the afternoon on a weekday and felt like the only 1 at times. Yet, videos play on auto loop. As some of the videos were longer, I also had to wait quite a while to fully enjoy each of the pieces. More often than not, people would walk by without stopping for long.

Conversations about gender are person specific and not easily understood without starting from the intended artists' beginning. For this reason, it was disappointing for me on various levels.
Stopped by here on a whim and was glad we did. My kids loved the displays and the area upstairs where they could make their own art. I'm sure we will be returning at some point in time.

reviews.text: The app is easy to use but I do feel like there could be improvements. Apparently the bluetooth doesn't work, so can't use a headset during the video calls. If other person has slow & glitchy connection, you waste time trying to figure out what's being said. I met a nice guy but found out he was 2 hours away from me🙁. Hope I get closer matches next time.

The have speed dating events with locals but every time I’ve done one none of the local listed you can talk to. The only people they connect you with are out of state mostly in a different time zone. Don’t waste your time or money with them.
I like this service a lot. Just want you to fix the swiping feature, sometimes I get repeating profiles.
Nice app with free swipes! Like it more than Tinder
Where is the phone number on the website? Why can't I see any real events? Why are the only events online and so expensive?

properties.formatted_address: St. Louis, MO 63106, USA
properties.name: Loretta Hall Park

reviews.text: Awesome little park! Has a skate rink, a basketball court, a grass field, a playground, and restroom building. I love using the skating rink - it's level, smooth, and in good shape. Overall, the park is well kept and has never been crowded on any of my visits. Great for families. As far as I can tell, it's street parking only.
This park has a great looking skating rink that's fun for both kids and adults. Great playground and view of the St. Louis skyline.
I love this place I roller skate here alot but the city won't provide upkeep services at all
For the past 50 years neighborhood I grew up from 1968-1988 They celebrate every year minus Pandemic 2020 Great place to gather music , plenty of food to serve all walks of life , reminiscing etc

I grew up in Carr Square Village and went to Carr School, Franklin School and Vashon High School. We were a tight knit community and we loved one another. I felt safe and nurtured by my neighbors. Because of the Carr Square Village Community I am the successful confident woman I am today.

properties.adr_address: 1409 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1409 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: City Museum & Washington Avenue Parking St Louis

reviews.text: Very compact venue for the amount inside.  Expect to wait in lines for slides.  My granddaughter waited 20 minutes for the big slide.  Definitely don't recommend for kids under 3 or 4.  Limited areas to explore for the younger kids considering the admission
First time visiting and my kids, ranging from 2-10 , LOVED this place. Something for me each kid (and parents) to do! I wish our museum was more like this closer to home. We will def be back!

Do not miss it! This is not a museum, it's a gigantic interactive playground. Don't get me wrong, there are some exhibits, but they are lost among the myriad of themed play areas designed by local artists from recycled materials. Don't expect your standard monkey bars, see-saws and swing sets. At City Museum children can literally disappear into the walls and emerge from the ceiling or floor. A giant fish tank mesmerizes young and old while a ten story slide offers seemingly endless thrills. There is as much to do indoors as outdoors so weather is not an issue. If you are looking for an activity that will delight a two year old, a twelve year old and a twenty-two year old then this is your place. I have spent three days here and I still haven't seen everything there is to do. They also serve decent food and alcoholic beverages at reasonable prices. City Museum is a "must do" activity for any family that likes to have fun together.

It was neat, but there were so many people!  Museum is a bit misleading as it’s mostly a gigantic jungle gym (which was awesome! But packed with so many people).  There are a few exhibits packed away in small rooms and many other rooms were under construction.  Kids 7-10 will love it.  Their parents will likely be looking for the bar (there’s a bar).

The creativity and sense of adventure is embedded in all aspects of this unique building. I spent several hours there crawling underneath tunnels in the floor, running through a makeshift parkour/skate park. I could not have wished for a better time with my young family and friends and it made me feeling like a child again myself!

editorial_summary.overview: Long-standing 105-acre outdoor park filled with contemporary art that hosts concerts & events.

properties.formatted_address: 12580 Rott Rd, Sappington, MO 63127, USA
properties.name: Laumeier Sculpture Park

reviews.text: At the front of the park is the art gallery where very exquisite art was on display! There were a lot of beautiful art filled with knowledgeable books that were sold at a cost of $5 which are fun table pieces to have for friends! The party leads down into fun filled trails, beautiful art throughout the park, and knowledgeable plaques posted to learn more about the artist and the reason behind the style of art displayed! Beautiful scenery mixed with incredibly large sized art all throughout the park makes for an otter world experience filled with the collision of raw nature and intellectual art! Have fun and soak up the beautiful weather right now!

What a lovely park!   Such a nice area to spend time outdoors and walk -  and the sculptures make it so much more interesting.   Great place for a picnic too.  Some of the sculptures are pretty neat.  And free admission.  We only stayed an hour but you could easily stay for several hours if you want to get your steps in.

Pretty neat little place and it's free. Came here for a quick walk because I was in the area and was able to check out some of the interesting structures that they had on display. Quite family friendly and ample parking. The trails mostly don't have shade so don't come on a hot day.

What a beautiful park!  Huge sculptures everywhere that you look.  It is really a sight to see.  The grounds are trimmed and visitors center is helpful.  Make sure to grab a map while in the center. Truly a neat place.
A Route 66 stop on my journey.  It's free to walk around the grounds and dog friendly. There are many large sculptures to see and appreciate. Many photo ops. Definitely worth a stop.

properties.adr_address: 13002 Bellefontaine Rd, St. Louis, MO 63138-1606, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Site of a former military installation on 300+ riverfront acres with trails, wetlands & wildlife.

properties.formatted_address: 13002 Bellefontaine Rd, St. Louis, MO 63138, USA
properties.name: Fort Belle Fontaine

reviews.text:
Hiked the loop trail with a group of 6, plus my pup for an early Saturday afternoon visit in November 2021. It measured 4.34 miles with an elevation gain of 298 feet and completed it in under 2 hours. We took a very leisurely pace to enjoy the fall colors, sit beside the river, and explore the fort itself.

Highly recommend for an easy and decently brief scenic hike close to the city.

It was nice to see a security guard on post keeping an eye on a historical location. The trails are well kept. Deer were abundant! Got within 10ft of a doe while walking the trail. Beautiful views. Grounds are well kept.

Never knew about this place until St. Louis County Parks advertised a hike and eagle watch event on Facebook. 01.21.23 Hike was amazing! Oh, thanks also for the special treat of hot chocolate. 😊 Huge thank you to the volunteers who led an informative walk through the grounds, down to Coldwater Creek, then along the Missouri River. If you are a novice hiker no worries. Walk was mostly flat with exception of getting down to the creek, and even then the decline was gradual. A beautiful place with lots of history. Can't wait to go back during  spring, summer, and fall to explore.

I agree with others, this is a hidden gem! The various ruins, Missouri river and also the beautiful exposed bedrock along Cold Water creek were unexpected!
I wish there was more historical info on the various ruins, but I understand park funding isn’t the best.
My only issue was a LOT of dog poop on the trails (and dog poop bags, empty and full) especially the first 1/4 mile. I am assuming that’s bc there is a police dog training school nearby but noted this is a trail heavily used by dog owners too.

This place was a real surprise the limestone staircase is pretty cool, but what I thought was even cooler was the limestone riverbank where my dog and I found a cavernous stream. All of the stonework was added using onsite limestone in the 30's as a new deal project, interesting 🤔

properties.adr_address: 6727 Heege Rd, St. Louis, MO 63123-2647, USA
properties.formatted_address: 6727 Heege Rd, St. Louis, MO 63123, USA
properties.name: Tower Tee Golf

reviews.text: Had a family fun day at the Top Tracer Bays this afternoon.  There were 7 of us.  Ages 10 to, well, let’s just say several times that number, and we all had a great time. The cost was very reasonable. The facility is spotless. The staff are so friendly and helpful.  Been a patron of Tower Tee for a LONG time but this new facility is absolutely amazing!

I was finally able to play the newly renovated Tower Tee today. And I must say I was thoroughly impressed. The driving range has two levels, stalls with shot tracers, a chipping area. The range balls are Bridgestone and feel/hit nicely.  There is also a putt-putt course, but not nearly as interesting as the old one.

The pro shop is a finer one you will find anywhere around.

There is a playground for the kids and, of course the batting cages.

Now to the course itself and the reason this isn't a 5 star review...

The new course is a 9 hole course as opposed to the old 18 hole course.  The greens were in excellent shape and the course overall was well manicured and a considerable upgrade from old TT.  From the back tees most holes play between 75 to 100 yards. Holes 5 and 9 are longer and you would be wise to bring a longer club along just for them. The difficulty comes into play not from the course or it's excellent and well placed hazards (or the mature trees), but from the fact that the "footgolf" course plays within the same space as the golf course!  There were NUMEROUS times that an errant shot from a footballer would come rolling across the greens mid-putt.  Secondly, they play from the same tees as the golfers, making for some very slow play. (We played behind two groups of footballers, one was an adult foursome, and another with 6 kids and 1 adult).  Additionally, it took a minute for us to determine which flags were for golf as opposed to footgolf.

Suggestion:  There is a pretty large area down the hill (where the old course back nine was) that could've been used for the footballers.  Right now it looks to be a bunch of weeds.

We did not indulge, but there is food and drinks available, including a "cold and frosty".

Overall I enjoyed the experience and will definitely be returning. I'm very glad you're back Tower Tee.  And many thanks to the owners who rescued the course where I learned to play this beloved game.

This place is awesome now. Full upgrade! To tracer bays, a ton of other hitting bays, a putting course, a playground, batting cages, a bar, food, and soon to be huge short game area. Family friendly, and the staff is great

Wow super impressed with this place! We had a surprise 60th birthday party here and they were so accommodating! Everyone is so friendly and helpful. They also are kid friendly. Clean and lots of activities. We will be back thank you for a great experience!!
Practiced years ago here.  Just took Friends grandson Jonah to practice hitting baseballs.   I was totally shocked when I pulled in.  This place  is awesome!!  So much fun !!

properties.adr_address: 601 Clark Ave, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Buzzing, sports-themed district by Busch Stadium with restaurants, bars & nightlife venues.

properties.formatted_address: 601 Clark Ave, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Ballpark Village

reviews.text: I didn’t grow up watching baseball. In fact, I didn’t live in St. Louis until I was 18 years old, and I enjoyed the games, but I had no desire to arrive early or leave late. Ballpark Village came along and really added to the whole game day experience for me. These days, I park here, eat here, shop here, and just walk around to enjoy the atmosphere. I’m always early for games, and hang around long after they’re over because there’s a place that is fun to hang out at, and it feels safe. My family and I pretty much enjoy everything that Ballpark Village has to offer, and I definitely recommend you check it out whether you’re headed to a game or not!

Although the team didn't make the playoffs, and we're done for the season on our visit, there was still an air of an amazing place to hang out for a game.  We had the cheeseburger tots...FANTASTIC! A wide variety of beers on tap, with a wall of spirits to suit your fancy...definitely worth the visit, will be back during the season for sure next visit!!

Great ballpark district. Very well put together. A lot of food and drink locations to pick from and it all seems very clean, safe and fun. The bud house is huge! Plenty of activities and staff to keep the beer flowing

The Cards were playing out of town, we wanted to do something downtown as a pit stop passing through. We popped in to grab lunch what a great experience. Game was on the jumbo Tron, big comfy booths, beer pong tables, something for the whole family. Will highly recommend.

Amazing area. Great for watching any sports from Saturday College football, Sunday NFL, Hockey, and certainly St Louis Cardinals Baseball. The outdoor concert area is large enough to hold several hundred people without feeling completely packed. Inside there are a couple of levels with different restaurants/ bars. There are all types of food available.  There's always Anheuser-Busch products on tap. There's even Michelob Golden Light on Tap there.

properties.adr_address: 999 N 2nd St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Refined quarters in a high-end casino property with 2 hotels & a spa, plus indoor & outdoor pools.

properties.formatted_address: 999 N 2nd St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Horseshoe St. Louis

reviews.text: Check in time is 4 pm. We arrived about 4:50 pm. Room was not ready. We had dinner reservations at 6:30 at a nearby restaurant.  We had to get ready in the hotel lobby bathroom. Beyond difficult. Staff at front desk, including manager, were very polite and trying to get us in our room. It took well over an hour but we finally got into our room. Room was nice and spacious. Beds were comfy. We were able to get a late checkout as well. Very accommodating staff.  We will definitely be back.

I noticed reviews mentioning a lack of cleanliness but this wasn't our experience at all. we had a corner suite which was perfectly clean and tidy upon check in. the only reason I gave 4 of 5 stars is the lack of room service but that figures; they want you to go over and spend money at the Casino and restaurants... which we did and had a great time

My boyfriend and I visited the casino and left within an hour of arriving. The staff was nice; however, the ambiance did not meet our expectations. Nothing specific happened, but I’m sure other females can understand when I say the vibe was off. I felt uneasy as a woman walking through the casino, even while next to my boyfriend.

Room was obviously not clean with tissues under the nightstand and a sock under the dresser, fairly obvious things to miss. Shower wouldn't work properly and the whole place smell like cigarettes. I was offered two other separate rooms which were even dirtier upon an inspection of me and the front desk. After not being able to find me a suitable accommodation they were only able to offer me half off if I were to stay and rough it through the night, or a full reimbursement if I pack my things and leave.

I am a Caesar's Diamond rewards member and had my room for 2 nights comped. The Hotel wasn't anything special but it was enough to stay there for the 2 nights. My view from the hotel was of a homeless camp right next to the river. The Casino was a different story though. I played blackjack and the tables were pretty nasty. I saw a bunch of hair from who knows where on the table where I was trying to place bets. They should probably clean the tables more often. They had a new dealer that was still training but it seemed like it took forever to get anywhere when at the table. Other dealers didn't seem as friendly as other places I've gambled. I went to the rewards counter to try and get my 5x tier registered during the time it said and they told me I could not do that even when showing them my offer on my phone.  Also watch out for people trying to scam you here. There was a guy going around asking if you have cash app to try and get you to pull money out of the ATM for them. Just don't do it because there are ways you can have that money taken away by cash app, look up cash app scams if you don't believe me.  Also make sure to check if there is any money in the slot machine before you go up and play. I had a lady on her phone at a slot machine 30 ft away from the one I was at tell me she had .25 cents in that machine that she was still on it while she was at a totally different machine on the phone talking. I think they try to scam that way as well since there wasn't anything in that machine but she kept telling me there was money on it. I told her I'd have them check the cameras if it was a big deal and she shut up. She wasn't worth fight over .25 cents. But watch out for people trying to pull fast ones here at this casino.

Final thoughts:  Even though this place made a lot off me; my mom and I still enjoyed the time we could spend together on our Christmas break. Next time I think I will just use the comp hotel room and enjoy the city. But don't think I will step foot inside that casino again after all the nonsense I endured there. Even though the security presence is very big and you feel somewhat safe there. I'll keep my money to gamble at the Horseshoe I live by In Indianapolis.

Caesars I know you can do better with this place as of November the payout was 89% no wonder why I lost as much as I did. Even though it's not a very nice part of town; please try to square this place away a little more and it might be a decent casino.

properties.adr_address: 2505 St Louis Ave, St. Louis, MO 63106-2324, USA
properties.formatted_address: 2505 St Louis Ave, St. Louis, MO 63106, USA
properties.name: Griot Museum of Black History

reviews.text: A very interesting museum with unique exhibits that are a mix of entertaining and moving. The Josephine Baker exhibit is beautiful. While the exhibit about the slave trade and the middle passage was heart wrenching and thought provoking. Definitely one of the more unique attractions of St Louis.
The wax exhibit was excellent.the story telling was very informative I learn a lot of history there I will go back again if I am ever in town. Unfortunately we are not aloud to take pictures.

The content and education were very detailed and educational. From a servicing standpoint (which I'm big on) the brunette at the front desk didn't seem to be the best for the job. Lazy and lack of empathy is what I felt from her. Also their website needs to clarify that reservations are required as many visitors had no clue.
Took the kids for a dose of black history. It was eye opening for them. Great experience, bought a cook homemade bracelet.

My two 6yr olds were bored and couldn't quite understand ( could be a little more interactive).  The three yr old was afraid and only wanted to color in the hallway.  But my 9yr old found it Very Interesting.  I even Learned a few things while reading to Them 😊.

properties.adr_address: 50 N Leonor K Sullivan Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.formatted_address: 50 N Leonor K Sullivan Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Gateway Helicopter Tours Inc

reviews.text: Back 50 years ago I worked in the oil exploration in the Amazon jungle and have hundreds of hours as a passenger in a helicopter so the ride itself was nothing new. However it was enjoyable. They have four different flights at different price points. We got the most expensive one which lasted about 20 minutes and flew us all around St. Louis. Well worth the money we spent. A very enjoyable experience. Just come on down to the dock and go inside the building and then five minutes later you’ll be up in the air

These folks run a wonderful helicopter tour conveniently located right next to the Gateway Arch. The shortest tour, around 3 minutes in the area, is rather affordable at $48. It provided some exceptionally unique views of the St Louis skyline and I highly recommend giving it a try
Mack you were great! Everyone and everything was.  The only disappointment was we were promised some Top Gun Maverick stuff and nothing... LOL JK if you get a chance try it! #CherryPopped LOL
Ohhhh my goodness.  We had a wonderful time.  It was perfect 🥰.  My first helicopter ride and it was AMAZING 👏.  The pilot was Awesome
Everyone was really nice and welcoming! That was my first helicopter ride and it was amazing! We had a lot of fun on the 8 min ride.

properties.adr_address: 615 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63101, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Museum featuring interactive exhibits focused on the history of blues music, plus a theater.

properties.formatted_address: 615 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63101, USA
properties.name: National Blues Museum

reviews.text:
Incredible way to spend an afternoon! Give yourself more than an hour so you can read and listen all you like.

So much history. Great tunes. Interactive exhibits. Reminders of musicians you've loved and forgotten over the years.

The museum is taking COVID precautions and you're asked to book tickets starting at a particular time and to wear a face mask.

The employee at the front desk was so genuinely sweet and really brightened my day.

Small but so well done! So many interactive exhibits you can spend hours just playing around with those. Several great films to watch. Great displays and the staff were wonderful, over the top friendly! I was very surprised with the gift shop. Finding a gift shop that is not overpriced is a shock these days. If you are in the city make the time to stop in. Totally worth the time. Plus the location is great for food and drinks afterwards.

I had a blast . Ms Debra @ the front desk really looked out for us. She allow my friend and I to bring our loaded Bicycles inside so we could enjoy the museum. Very kinda staff and very lovely experience. Will go back again in the future for some refreshing. ✌🏽

I was there during museum hours.  It is an interactive museum with the history of blues from Africa to current times and it’s impact on different genres of music .   You can even write and mix your own blues song thanks to Jack White.

We were in town for the weekend and stopped into the Museum spur of the moment. It was $15/adult ticket. There was no wait. First thing we did was use the women's restroom. Most of the soap dispensers were out of soap and the restroom was quite messy considering at the time we entered we were the only 2 guests. The actual museum expected was nice. It is a self-guided tour. It takes you through the different decades of jazz music from the Jim Crow era to current day. There are also some hands on exhibits to try. Definitely worth a visit at least once.
